00:41:01.310 --> 00:41:09.670
&gt;&gt; T. C. Boyle: Sure. What a great question.
For everybody else who's not hearing this

00:41:09.670 --> 00:41:18.789
question, there's a lot of praise involved.
I mean, we've just had several paragraphs

00:41:18.789 --> 00:41:23.349
of praise of how wonderful I am.

00:41:23.349 --> 00:41:24.349
[laughter]

00:41:24.349 --> 00:41:32.910
But I won't get into that. It's a question
about the structure of 'The Women', my last

00:41:32.910 --> 00:41:39.819
novel before this, which deals with the entire
life and career of Frank Lloyd Wright, primarily

00:41:39.819 --> 00:41:46.450
though, as seen through the point of view
of his four women in his life: his mistress

00:41:46.450 --> 00:41:51.269
and his three wives. And it also runs backwards
so that you begin with his last wife and go

00:41:51.269 --> 00:41:53.190
down the ladder to the death of Mamah.

00:41:53.190 --> 00:42:00.480
Well, for obvious reasons, I could then end
climactically with the murder of Martha Borthwick

00:42:00.480 --> 00:42:04.180
Cheney. She was killed with a hatchet by a
crazed servant. Her two children were killed,

00:42:04.180 --> 00:42:05.270
also. And also several other workers and the
house was burned down. What's so interesting,

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:11.579
as you say, is that Frank Lloyd Wright was
not there that day because he was doing the

00:42:11.579 --> 00:42:16.349
Midway Gardens in Chicago and commuting back
and forth. And he was trying to get this thing

00:42:16.349 --> 00:42:17.749
onto deadline and get it built.

00:42:17.749 --> 00:42:21.980
Had he been there, he well could have been
killed and there would have been nothing beyond

00:42:21.980 --> 00:42:29.630
1914. So there's all of that. Well, as soon
as I discovered this structure, and of course,

00:42:29.630 --> 00:42:30.650
I had a structural idea in the beginning,
which I didn't have with this cause each one

00:42:30.650 --> 00:42:31.650
is different.

00:42:31.650 --> 00:42:32.650
[pause]

00:42:32.650 --> 00:42:33.650
I could meditate on what love relationships
are. How, not me, of course, but I'm sure

00:42:33.650 --> 00:42:45.029
all of you maybe had more than one relationship
in your life, where you're in love and it's

00:42:45.029 --> 00:42:46.029
this great thing.

00:42:46.029 --> 00:42:50.509
You wanna spend every second with your inamorata
and it's so great. But maybe after a while,

00:42:50.509 --> 00:42:55.499
you fall apart and maybe it goes sour. Maybe
it even gets antagonistic. So I was able to

00:42:55.499 --> 00:42:57.200
show, by going backwards, each of them. Like,
to begin with, Olgivanna, his last wife was

00:42:57.200 --> 00:43:04.430
there and he's in love with her, but he's
being pursued by his previous wife, Miriam.

00:43:04.430 --> 00:43:05.869
Miriam is this virago. She's a lunatic. She's
horrible. But then, as we go backwards, we

00:43:05.869 --> 00:43:07.569
see Miriam in a new light, when he first meets
her and she's so sexy and enchanting and that

00:43:07.569 --> 00:43:09.239
enables me to play with the idea of what relationships
are.

00:43:09.239 --> 00:43:15.410
Then again, I'm using real material. I love
the real history, or the real biology. I'm

00:43:15.410 --> 00:43:19.500
just dramatizing it. So Miriam, in real life,
and in my telling, came to Frank Lloyd Wright

00:43:19.500 --> 00:43:21.190
and after the death of Mamah. She'd been murdered.
Taliesin Center had been burned down. He got

00:43:21.190 --> 00:43:22.580
lots of sympathy. He got letters from all
over the world, thousands of them.

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:24.270
'Cause he was pretty well-known at this point.
One came from Miriam Maude Noel. She was around

00:43:24.270 --> 00:43:28.502
his age, which was late 40s at that time.
She was an elegant and beautiful woman.

00:43:28.502 --> 00:43:29.502
[pause]

00:43:29.502 --> 00:43:30.502
Widowed. She'd been living in Paris for the
last ten years. But World War I drove her

00:43:30.502 --> 00:43:31.502
back to live in this miserable room in Chicago
with her daughter.

00:43:31.502 --> 00:43:32.502
And he liked her letter so much, he agreed
to meet with her on Christmas Eve, in his

00:43:32.502 --> 00:43:37.609
office in Chicago, their first meeting. And
she swept in wearing her sealskin coat and

00:43:37.609 --> 00:43:47.859
this beautiful hat and these boas and everything
else and had a lorgnette and a cigarette in

00:43:47.859 --> 00:43:54.299
a holder. And she just talked breathlessly
to him about love and passion and poetry and

00:43:54.299 --> 00:43:57.560
everything else, on and on and on. He was
mesmerized by her.

00:43:57.560 --> 00:44:00.390
Then she paused for breath and said, "So,
how do you like me?" And he said, "I've never

00:44:00.390 --> 00:44:02.390
seen anything like you." Boom! Wow, that was
it. What a relationship. Also, I got this

00:44:02.390 --> 00:44:07.220
information from his own autobiography. But
what do you do with it? And I just structured

00:44:07.220 --> 00:44:11.960
it. So, each one is different and each one
has its own [audience member sneezes] [ ]. And

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:13.579
you're right to ask this question because
in that case, I had a structural idea to begin

00:44:13.579 --> 00:44:14.579
with.

00:44:14.579 --> 00:44:15.579
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #4: So, which of the
books have [audience member coughs] less of

00:44:15.579 --> 00:44:16.579
that historical aspect? I can think of maybe
