00:44:16.579 --> 00:44:17.579
of them have some kind of factual base that
you're drawing from?

00:44:17.579 --> 00:44:26.650
&gt;&gt; T. C. Boyle: The question is which of the
books [audience member coughs] have less of

00:44:26.650 --> 00:44:31.280
the history or less of factual? I rotate always
between different sorts of things, just to

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:32.660
keep myself fresh and to keep the audience
fresh. So that novels that are just whole

00:44:32.660 --> 00:44:33.660
cloth are things like 'East Is East' set in
Georgia. Or there's 'The Writer's Colony'

00:44:33.660 --> 00:44:34.660
set in Japan.

00:44:34.660 --> 00:44:35.660
Most recently,[pause] 'A Friend of the Earth'.
'A Friend of the Earth', which precedes this,

00:44:35.660 --> 00:44:36.660
is also about environmental issues; the year
2000 on global warming, which projects into

00:44:36.660 --> 00:44:37.900
2025. And that is just us. And so two of the
stories.

00:44:37.900 --> 00:44:38.900
Some stories require some research, 'cause
I set stories anywhere. I have no limitations.

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:39.900
I can set a story anywhere on earth. And some
are just experiences. It requires nothing.

00:44:39.900 --> 00:44:40.900
Just you are inspired. You do it. I'll give
you an example. I wrote a story a few years

00:44:40.900 --> 00:44:43.599
back that the New Yorker published and it
was called 'Swept Away'. It's a very whimsical

00:44:43.599 --> 00:44:44.599
story.

00:44:44.599 --> 00:44:49.660
I had read that the windiest place in the
world is the Shetland Islands of Scotland.

00:44:49.660 --> 00:44:51.349
Kids, little kids get spun down the street,
cats, flower pots. It's always windy there.

00:44:51.349 --> 00:44:52.349
So what fun! What would that be like? So I
wrote a love story. It's about an American

00:44:52.349 --> 00:44:53.349
ornithologist who comes to study the birds.
She's kind of pretty. She's wearing a little

00:44:53.349 --> 00:44:54.349
tartan skirt that she's bought at the tourist
shop. She's got black leggings and she's kind

00:44:54.349 --> 00:44:55.349
of cute. She's just got off the ferry, got
her backpack full of cameras and stuff. And

00:44:55.349 --> 00:44:56.349
she's walking up the main street. And behind
the window of the main street are all the

00:44:56.349 --> 00:45:01.530
local slugs who live there drinking beer.
And it turns out that one of them is Robbie

00:45:01.530 --> 00:45:06.660
Bakey and he's never had a girlfriend in his
life. He's never done anything with his life.

00:45:06.660 --> 00:45:08.290
He's lived on his family's sheep ranch and
so on.

00:45:08.290 --> 00:45:09.839
And his cat is out there trying to catch pigeons.
It's a big cat, not like the cats we were

00:45:09.839 --> 00:45:10.839
talking about, the foxes we were talking about.
This is a 14-pound cat. It's blown off by

00:45:10.839 --> 00:45:11.839
a gust and it cracks Julie [ ] right in the
head and she's knocked out unconscious on

00:45:11.839 --> 00:45:12.839
the road. And at that point, old Duncan Stauer,
the oldest guy on the island, is coming in

00:45:12.839 --> 00:45:16.030
his car, his ancient car, going ten miles
an hour right for her and Robbie Bakey runs

00:45:16.030 --> 00:45:17.059
out and saves her.

00:45:17.059 --> 00:45:18.190
And so, the romance starts. All right. Well,
this has a lot of local color, this story.

00:45:18.190 --> 00:45:19.619
Shetland Islands. So, two years later the
local magazine on the Shetland Islands, 'The

00:45:19.619 --> 00:45:21.430
Shetlander', asked me if they could reprint
the story because it was so great and they

00:45:21.430 --> 00:45:23.810
wondered how many years I lived in the Shetland
Islands. And I had to point out that I had

00:45:23.810 --> 00:45:25.940
never actually been to the Shetland Islands.
But I had been to the Arctic Coast of Scotland

00:45:25.940 --> 00:45:27.450
once in Oban and I nearly froze to death.
That was enough.

00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:28.450
And the rest is invented. So I got lots of
details of the Islands, right down to names

00:45:28.450 --> 00:45:29.450
of characters and so on. And faked it. That's
what it's about. It's an improvisation. It's

00:45:29.450 --> 00:45:30.450
a seduction of view. I am inviting you into
this world for you to believe in.

00:45:30.450 --> 00:45:31.450
But sometimes, as with the details of this
or with the Frank Lloyd Wright book, the historical

00:45:31.450 --> 00:45:32.519
details, I love the history so much. Or here
the ecology, that I'm sort of instructing

00:45:32.519 --> 00:45:33.519
you in it. There've been over 1006 books written
about Frank Lloyd Wright. I never realized

00:45:33.519 --> 00:45:36.420
the extent of the cult of him until I went
to write this book, wrote this book. But if

00:45:36.420 --> 00:45:37.490
you've never read any of them and know nothing
about him, you can read this novel and it's

00:45:37.490 --> 00:45:38.490
all true; all the facts are true.

00:45:38.490 --> 00:45:39.490
But, of course, I'm playing it for my own
purposes and dramatizing it. You know, history

00:45:39.490 --> 00:45:40.490
is wonderful, but it doesn't tell you what
people were thinking. You just heard a day

00:45:40.490 --> 00:45:41.490
of Lajoy for instance. You're in his head.
You get an idea of what he's thinking. You

00:45:41.490 --> 00:45:42.490
don't get that necessarily from history. So
my fun by going to some of these books is

00:45:42.490 --> 00:45:43.490
to dramatize them. What was it like? [pause]
The first book I wrote in Santa Barbara. It's

00:45:43.490 --> 00:45:44.490
called 'Riven Rock'.

00:45:44.490 --> 00:45:45.490
I figured I would need to know some of the
history of the place I just moved to. 'Riven

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:46.490
Rock is set at the turn of the last century,
and it deals with Stanley McCormick. He was

00:45:46.490 --> 00:45:47.490
the heir to the McCormick reaper, the fortune.
A millionaire. He had a big 35-acre estate

00:45:47.490 --> 00:45:48.490
and so on. When he was in his late 20s, he
married a woman, also in her late 20s, Catherine

00:45:48.490 --> 00:45:49.490
Dexter McCormick, an amazing beauty and also
very, very wealthy. First female graduate

00:45:49.490 --> 00:45:50.490
in the sciences at MIT. And I would say he's
very handsome; tall, handsome guy, wealthy,

00:45:50.490 --> 00:45:51.490
bright-thinking.

00:45:51.490 --> 00:45:52.490
The problem is he had a mental problem, which
was beginning to become paranoia. He was a

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:53.490
schizophrenic. Catherine made the great mistake
that many women do, thinking, "Well, you know,

00:45:53.490 --> 00:45:54.490
he's a little squirrely, but if I get him
away from his mother, I think I can straighten

00:45:54.490 --> 00:45:55.490
him out." Catastrophically wrong. It was just
the most horrendous marriage in history. To

00:45:55.490 --> 00:45:56.490
just give one detail. They never consummated
the marriage.

00:45:56.490 --> 00:45:57.490
Stanley was incapable. He became, what was
called a 'sexual maniac'. For 20 years, he

00:45:57.490 --> 00:45:58.490
had to be locked in Riven Rock, away from
everybody because any woman he saw, he would

00:45:58.490 --> 00:45:59.490
assault immediately. Not necessarily sexually,
but just assault. He was that crazy. And I

00:45:59.490 --> 00:46:00.490
think it was because having to be intimate
was too much for him to stand and it made

00:46:00.490 --> 00:46:01.490
his mental problems more full-blown.

00:46:01.490 --> 00:46:02.490
And if you really want to hear horror, and
this is true. On the day they were married,

00:46:02.490 --> 00:46:03.490
at her chateau in Geneva, which is now the
American Embassy. And he was early advocate

00:46:03.490 --> 00:46:04.490
of motor cars, 1905. Their honeymoon was a
month motoring through France. Two other individuals

00:46:04.490 --> 00:46:05.490
came with them. His mother and her mother.
How could you make this stuff up? It is so

00:46:05.490 --> 00:46:06.490
fabulous. And so, to conclude all of this,
I will say, people ask me about this book.

00:46:06.490 --> 00:46:07.490
They said, "How do you know that the marriage
was unconsummated?" It's easy. I wrote the

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:08.490
book.

00:46:08.490 --> 00:46:09.490
[laughter]

00:46:09.490 --> 00:46:10.490
So, thank you very much.

